\begin_layout Abstract
As robots become increasingly prevalent in environments with humans across
 contexts, whether social or work, there is a need to understand human-robot
 interaction (HRI) to build strong and effective relationships.
 The motivation for this project stems from the existing and projected future
 collaboration between robots and crew in space, as crew time is the most
 precious resource, and offloading tasks to a robot partner would be invaluable.
 There are several aspects of HRI and the focus of this paper will be the
 relationship between path planning and proxemics, or social distance, which
 is the comfortable, physical distance between two parties.
 This project will investigate aspects of path planning and execution when
 proxemics are considered by simulating an autonomous, monitoring robot.
 The three-factorial experimental design encompasses path planning (cost
 function, artificial potential field), task type (direct path, waypoints,
 monitoring), and crew configuration (one person, two opposing, four with
 clustering, and random generation).
 The evaluation criteria will examine the trade off between efficiency and
 human comfort.
\end_layout

