\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 graph search method, introduced by Hart in 1968, uses a heuristic cost
 approximation to find optimal paths between nodes on a graph 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hart1968formal"

\end_inset

.
 For navigational applications of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

, positions in the environment are discretized and mapped to nodes on a
 graph, with connections to the neighboring positions.
 Nodes can be traversed by taking an action with an associated cost.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 algorithm uses a heuristic search technique to find an optimal set of actions
 to move from the starting node to the goal node.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 is not well suited for real-time navigation because it does not incorporate
 dynamics of the robot or its environment and may not be able to replan
 quickly enough to update based on those changes.
 Additionally on physical systems, paths generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 would need to be tracked using a lower-level controller.
 Variations on 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 and other algorithms based on similar principles have been used to address
 some of those challenges (Refer to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kirby2009companion,stentz1994d,koenig2004lifelong"

\end_inset

), but 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 is still considered a standard technique for path planning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Artificial Potential Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The APF method for robot navigation was introduced by Khatib in the 1980's
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "khatib1986real"

\end_inset

.
 APF is a reactive navigation method that models the robot as a particle
 driven by a potential field.
 In APF, a potential field is mapped onto the environment based on the position
 of goals and obstacles.
 Goals are incorporated as negative (attractive) potentials, while obstacles
 have associated positive (repulsive) potentials.
 Then, the desired acceleration of the robot is set as a modeled force equal
 to the negative gradient of the potential field.
 In this way, the robot drives away from obstacles and towards the goal.
 This method is relatively simple to implement and is well suited for real-time
 navigation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main limitations of APF  come from the locality of the behavior, such
 as becoming trapped in local minima or oscillating near obstacles due to
 local extrema 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "koren1991potential"

\end_inset

.
 The APF method cannot provide any guarantee of global optimality, since
 the control scheme is inherently local.
 In order to address these challenges, one may try to carefully formulate
 the potentials associated with obstacles and goal positions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ge2000new"

\end_inset

.
 Another approach is to incorporate a hierarchical supervisor that switches
 to another navigation method if it detects the APF controller has become
 caught at a local minima, which has the main drawback of added complexity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yun1997wall,mabrouk2008solving"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

