\begin_layout Subsection
Artificial Potential Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In APF, the robot is modelled as a particle driven by a potential field.
 The potential field is linear, so the total potential at each point is
 is the sum of the different components
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(x_{r},y_{y}\right)=\sum U_{i}\left(x_{r},y_{y}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the force acting on the robot is the partial derivative of the potential
 field with respect to each direction with the addition of a damping term
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{x} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{r}}U\left(x_{r},y_{y}\right)-bv_{x}\\
F_{y} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial y_{r}}U\left(x_{r},y_{y}\right)-bv_{y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The motion of robot is then determined by the dynamic and kinematic constraints
 for two dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}v_{x} & =\frac{1}{m}F_{x}\\
\frac{d}{dt}v_{y} & =\frac{1}{m}F_{y}\\
\frac{d}{dt}x_{r} & =v_{x}\\
\frac{d}{dt}y_{r} & =v_{y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In many APF simulations, damping in the overall system is included in the
 dynamic model of the mobile robot, caused by losses such as friction.
 We chose to consider the damping as a tunable parameter in the scheme navigatio
n for two reasons.
 First, we did not have a good model for the drag Astrobee would encounter
 while moving in the module, making it difficult to justify the choice of
 a parameter.
 Second, since Astrobee is travelling at low velocities, additional damping
 in the navigation system may need to be added to achieve a desirable performanc
e, so we could consider the the total damping as a design parameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The repulsive potential field associated with the module boundary is a gaussian
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}U_{\text{wall}}\left(x_{r},y_{r}\right) & =\exp\left[-\frac{\left(x_{r}-w\right)^{2}}{2\sigma_{w}^{2}}\right]+\exp\left[-\frac{\left(y_{r}-h\right)^{2}}{2\sigma_{w}^{2}}\right]\\
 & \qquad+\exp\left[-\frac{x_{r}^{2}}{2\sigma_{w}^{2}}\right]+\exp\left[-\frac{y_{r}^{2}}{2\sigma_{w}^{2}}\right]
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{r}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 coordinates of the robot, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are the width and height of the module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 is a width normalizing constant set to 0.15 so that the potential drops
 off to 1% of the peak value 1.5 robot lengths from a wall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The attractive potential field associated with the goal position is a combinatio
n conic and quadratic potential, two common goal models used in APF, defined
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{\text{goal}}\left(x_{r},y_{r}\right)=\begin{cases}
-kd^{2} & \text{ if }d<1.5l\\
-k\left(1.5l+d\right) & \text{ if }d\ge1.5l
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\sqrt{\left(x_{r}-x_{g}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{r}-y_{g}\right)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the distance between the robot and the goal and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is the side length of the robot.
 This potential acts as a spring force on the robot when the robot is close
 to the goal and as a constant attractive force when the robot is far.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The values for the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 were chosen by qualitatively evaluating the performance of APF for the
 simplest mission and crew configuration over a range of values.
 The values 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\unit[1]{N/m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\unit[5]{N\cdot s/m}$
\end_inset

 was chosen because the robot moved the fastest (0.25 m/s) without driving
 through the repulsive potential associated with the crew.
 This velocity is also a velocity that was considerd comfortable in the
 proxemic literature.
 This indicates that the forces associated with moving toward the goal,
 avoiding collisions with humans, and damping were acceptably tuned.
 However, this search was non-exhaustive and there may exist values which
 produce better path planning performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A* Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A* is a modification of Dijkstra's algorithm to find a lowest-cost path
 between two points on a directed graph, but it uses an additional heuristic
 to perform not just a breadth-first search, but a best-first search.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our general algorithm was implemented using a priority queue of potential
 paths, stored as lists of graph nodes with (x,y) coordinates and an associated
 velocity.
 As the robot traversed the discretized model, it looked at all possible
 nearest neighbors on the grid and a range of possible next velocities,
 assigning each possible next step a cost that depends on human proxemics
 and the robot's locaation and velocity.
 The cost function is described in more detail in Section 4.3: Human Avoidance
 Models.
 After the proxemic cost was calculated for each newest node in a path,
 each new path was added to the priority queue with 
\begin_inset Formula $Priority=(Cumulative\ proxemic\ cost)+(Heuristic)$
\end_inset

, where the heuristic is a function of location and velocity that emphasizes
 following the shortest path to the goal and travelling at a higher speed
 with different weights.
 The heuristic used in our simulations is described below in Section 4.2.1.
 Once each new potential path was added to the priority queue, the algorithm
 then selected the path with the lowest priority from the current queue,
 and it began the same process to extend the newly selected path.
 The algorithm returned a path when the edge of the robot reaches a distance
 of 1.2*the grid step size, which allowed the algorithm to recognize when
 the robot had reached its destination, still allowing for some uncertainty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Djikstra's Algorithm runs in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(N^{2})$
\end_inset

 time [CHECK AND CITE TEXTBOOK], but as the addition of a heuristic allows
 the algorithm to select the most likely path first, A* can often run in
 significantly less time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Heuristic and parameter determinations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Heuristic=\ \alpha*\left(Distance\ to\ goal\right)\ +\ \beta*\left(\dfrac{1}{New\ velocity}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We selected our heuristic to emphasize following the shortest path to the
 goal and travelling at a higher velocity, desirable traits that allow the
 robot to prioritize efficient use of fuel, power, and time.
 Both quantities were weighted with coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 following the manner found in Kirby's COMPANION algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kirbythesis"

\end_inset

, which allowed us to control the strength with which these priorities competed
 with the respect of proxemics, which was considered to have a weight of
 1 that was contributed by our Gaussian cost function described in 4.3.
 The weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 were chosen in a manner similar to the parameter selection in the APF case,
 where several instances of the same mission/crew combination were compared,
 and a reasonable answer was selected qualitatively.
 While more rigorous testing of parameters is recommended in further studies,
 our method of selection was deemed sufficient given the time limitations
 and scope of our study.
 Our results presented in Section 5 were found with weights of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Algorithm Modifications for Embodiment and Situatedness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We implemented our A* algorithm on a grid with a mesh size of the module
 length / 50, which corresponded to a 6.72
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distance between nodes in the x and y directions.
 The mesh size was selected qualitatively after some experimentation to
 find a balance between detail and computational time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The path extension step was implemented through consideration of the 9 nearest
 nodes with varying velocities, described below.
 Each path kept a list of nodes that had already been visited on the path,
 and only added nodes that hadn't been visited on the way to the current
 waypoint, in order to avoid pointless loops.
 Viability of nodes also considered potential robot collision, with hard
 constraints included that removed nodes a distance of the robot's working
 radius, defined as the distance from the center of the robot to a corner
 of the robot, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each step, the possible velocities for consideration were determined
 by the robot's inertia, maximum thrust, mass, and our hard-coded saftey
 constraints, which limited the maximum robot velocity to 0.5m/s at all times
 to protect crew comfort and spacecraft safety.
 Given a current velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}$
\end_inset

, possible velocities were determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{new}=\sqrt{{v_{0}^{2}\pm2as}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is our maximum acceleration, determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\dfrac{Maximum\ thrust}{Astrobee\ mass}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the distance travelled, with 
\begin_inset Formula $s=6.72"$
\end_inset

 for next nodes parellel to the module walls, or 
\begin_inset Formula $s=9.50"$
\end_inset

 for diagonal next nodes.
 Our considered velocity range was then determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{max}=min(Absolute\ max\ velocity,Max\ possible\ velocity)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{min}=max(0,Min\ possible\ velocity)$
\end_inset

, and five velocities (limited to mitigate the time taken for the code to
 run), equally spaced within that range, were considered at each viable
 next node.
 
\end_layout

