\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{\text{non-proxemic}}\left(x_{r},y_{r}\right)=\exp\left[-\frac{\left(x_{r}-x_{c}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{r}-y_{c}\right)^{2}}{2\sigma_{n}^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{r}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 coordinates of the robot, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{c}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 coordinates of the crew being modeled,
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an amplitude normalizing constant,
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a width normalizing constant.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{N}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 0.355 , so that the cost of a typical shoulder distance (14 inches) is
 half the cost as the center
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haslegrave1986characterizing"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proxemic model is the asymetric gaussian Kirby used to model personal
